name: citric acid production | protein feed, 100% crude | Cutoff, S
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/21412/documentation

Citric acid is produced by a submerged fermentation process which employs a strain of the micro-organism Aspergillus niger to convert sugar into citric acid: ;The carbohydrate substrate (glucose syrup), which is made from Chinese corn, is heat treated and inoculated with Aspergillus niger. After the fermentation the biological solids (mycelium) are removed. ;Then citric acid is recovered from the remaining broth and the resulting citric acid solution is purified by ion exchange and carbon treatment.;Finally the citric acid solution is evaporated, and citric acid is crystallised, dried and sieved. ;Energy (coal and electricity) is used in China. Coal is used to generate steam.

From cradle, i.e. including all upstream activities.

Production of citric acid including materials and energy uses, waste production and emissions. Infrastructure is estimated.
category: C:Manufacturing/20:Manufacture of chemicals and chemical products/201:Manufacture of basic chemicals, fertilizers and nitrogen compounds, plastics/2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals

processDocumentation.timeDescription: Time of cost calculation. According to producer data is valid for at least another 2 years until 2013.
processDocumentation.geographyDescription: The inventory is modelled for the Jilin region in China.
processDocumentation.samplingDescription: Data were derived from a detailed cost calculation of a planned, but not built production plant in the region of Jilin.

exchanges.description: Approximation. Fungus mycelium is a by-product of citric acid production. It is further used as animal feed mostly due to its fibre content. This exchange approximates the direct supply of protein feed from the fungus mycelium. DM and protein content of maize silage are employed as rough indicative values for fungus mycelium. The process is producing 0.069 kg of the fungus. DM assumed here 0.235 kg of DM per kg of wet mass. Crude protein is assumed to be 0.08 kg of protein per kg of DM.
